More SAS with Graphics¶

Creating SAS Data Sets from Procedure Output¶

Sometimes you may want to store the results of a procedure rather than just printing the output. Some procedures have built in options that allow you to store data with an OUT = statement. However, with ODS you can save almost any output as a SAS dataset.

The syntax to to do this is as follows:

ODS OUTPUT output-object = new-data-set;

The ODS Statement is not an option for a SAS DATA or PROC step. The ODS statement executes immediately, so it should be placed after the PROC statement, but before the next PROC, DATA, or RUN statement.

In [1]:
PROC TABULATE DATA=sashelp.class;
        CLASS Sex;
        VAR Height Weight;
        TABLE Sex, (Height Weight) * MEAN;
ODS OUTPUT Table = group_summaries;
RUN;
Out[1]:
SAS Output

The SAS System

Mean Mean
Sex 60.59 90.11
F
M 63.91 108.95

Customizing Titles and Footnotes¶

Titles and Footnotes can be be customized using the following syntax:

TITLE options 'text string' options 'text string2'  ... ;

FOOTNOTE options 'text string' options 'text string2'  ... ;

This allows use to customize chunks of code with different options.

Options¶

  • COLOR (specifies color for text)
  • BCOLOR (specifies color for the background of text)
  • HEIGHT (specifies the height of the text, can be in PT, IN, or CM)
  • JUSTIFY (text justification, LEFT, CENTER, RIGHT)
  • FONT (specifies font type)
  • BOLD (makes text bold)
  • ITALIC (makes text italic)
In [3]:
TITLE COLOR=BLUE 'Blue ' COLOR =BLACK ' Black ' COLOR = GRAY 'Gray ';
PROC PRINT DATA = sashelp.class;
RUN;

Style Options¶

In addition to changing the style template, individual options can also be specified. Using the following syntax (in a PROC PRINT statement).

PROC PRINT STYLE (location-list) = {style-attribute = value};
RUN;

The location-list options are:

  • DATA (all data cells)
  • HEADER (the column headers)
  • OBS (the data in OBS column)

The style-attributes are:

  • BACKGROUND (specifieds the background color, using any valid SAS color)
  • FONT_FACE (specifies font type, most devices support Times, Courier, Arial, Helvetica)
  • FONT_SIZE (specifies size of the font for text in cells, values 1 - 7)
  • FONT_WEIGHT (weight of font: BOLD, MEDIUM, LIGHT)
  • FOREGROUND (color of text in the cells)
  • JUST (RIGHT, CENTER, LEFT, D for Decimal)
In [5]:
TITLE;
PROC PRINT DATA= sashelp.class STYLE(DATA) = {FONT_STYLE = ITALIC FONT_WEIGHT = BOLD JUST = D};
RUN;

Stand-alone graphs¶

We have seen some graphs that are produced as part of SAS procedures, but we can also create stand alone graphs. Some options include:

Category Types
X vs. Y band, bubble, high-low, loess, regression, scatter, series
continuous box, density, histrogram
categorical dot, bar, line

PROC SGPLOT¶

PROC SGPLOT has a lot of similarities to the ggplot2 package in R. More details and documentation can be found at http://support.sas.com/documentation/cdl/en/grstatproc/62603/HTML/default/viewer.htm#sgplot-ov.htm.

There are four general classes of figures that can be constructed with PROC SGPLOT:

  1. Basic Plots (scatter plots, series plots)
  2. Fit and confidence plots (loess, regression lines)
  3. Distribution plots (box plots, histograms, density estimates)
  4. Categorization plots (dot plots, bar charts)
PROC SGPLOT syntax¶
PROC SGPLOT DATA=yourdata;
    YAXIS label="labelname" min = 0;
    VBAR variablename;
RUN;

VBAR specifies a vertical bar plot and there are many options of different types of figures that can be placed here. We will see several of them in coming slides.

You can also specify characteristics of the axes as well.

Controlling Features on SAS SGPLOT¶

  • What might we want to adjust with some of these graphics?
  • Axes
  • Titles
  • Reference lines
  • Legends
  • Insets (text annotation)
  • Point types
  • Line attributes
Axes¶

Specify either XAXIS or YAXIS. Full details are available here: http://support.sas.com/documentation/cdl/en/grstatproc/62603/HTML/default/viewer.htm#xaxis-stmt.htm

PROC SGPLOT DATA=yourdata;
    XAXIS options;

options include:

  • GRID (creates tick mark on the axis)
  • LABEL = 'textstring'
  • VALUES = (value-list) specifies value for tick marks. Values must be in parenthesis and can be either formatted as a list (0 5 10 15 20) or as a range (0 TO 20 BY 5).
Reference Lines¶

Reference lines are horizontal or vertical lines on a graph.

PROC SGPLOT DATA = yourdata;
    REFLINE values / options;

The values can be specified as a list or range. The options include:

  • AXIS = axis
  • LABEL = (label-list) Specifies one or more text strings to be used as labels
  • TRANSPARENCY = n, where n is between 0 and 1.
In [19]:
proc sgplot data=sashelp.stocks
  (where=(date >= "01jan2000"d and stock = "IBM"));
  title "Stock Trend";
  series x=date y=close;
  series x=date y=low;
  series x=date y=high;
  REFLINE 100/ AXIS = Y LABEL= ('$100') TRANSPARENCY=.5;
run;
Out[19]:
SAS Output

Legends¶

PROC SGPLOT procedures generate legends automatically, which can be good or bad depending on the situation. To change legends the following statement should be added to a SGPLOT procedures:

KEYLEGEND / options;

options include:

  • ACROSS = n (number of columns in the legend)
  • DOWN = n (number of rows in the legend)
  • LOCATION = value (location for legend, either INSIDE or OUTSIDE, the default)
  • NOBORDER (removes the border)
  • POSITION = value (specifies the position of the legend, TOP, TOPLEFT, TOPRIGHT, BOTTOM, BOTTOMLEFT, BOTTOMRIGHT, LEFT, RIGHT
Removing Legend¶
PROC SGPLOT DATA=yourdata NOAUTOLEGEND;
In [20]:
proc sgplot data=sashelp.stocks
  (where=(date >= "01jan2000"d and stock = "IBM"));
  title "Stock Trend for IBM";
  series x=date y=close;
  series x=date y=low;
  series x=date y=high;
  REFLINE 100/ AXIS = Y LABEL= ('$100') TRANSPARENCY=.5;
  KEYLEGEND/ DOWN=3 POSITION=TOPRIGHT LOCATION=INSIDE;
run;

INSETS (Text Annotation)¶

Insets can be added to the plot using the following syntax:

INSET 'text-string1' 'text-string2' / options;

Options include:

  • BORDER (adds a border)
  • POSITION = VALUE (TOP, TOPLEFT, TOPRIGHT, BOTTOM, BOTTOMLEFT, BOTTOMRIGHT, LEFT, RIGHT)
In [21]:
proc sgplot data=sashelp.stocks
  (where=(date >= "01jan2000"d and stock = "IBM"));
  title "Stock Trend";
  series x=date y=close;
  series x=date y=low;
  series x=date y=high;
  REFLINE 100/ AXIS = Y LABEL= ('$100') TRANSPARENCY=.5;
  INSET 'DOT COM Crash, 2000 - 2002' / POSITION=TOP BORDER;
run;

Additional Graph Attributes¶

There are other options that can be manipulated in SGPLOT by placing options ofter the the basic plot statement (and a slash). Some examples are shown below:

  • LABELATTRS = (attribute = value) specifies the appearance of the axis labels, options include COLOR, SIZE, STYLE and WEIGHT.
  • LINEATTRS = (attribute = value) appearance of line, options include COLOR, PATTERN, THICKNESS
  • MARKERATTRS = (attribute = value) appearance of maker, options include COLOR, SIZE, SYMBOL
  • VALUEATTRS = (attribute = value) appearance of axis tick labels, options include COLOR, SIZE, STYLE, WEIGHT.

The options for the attributes are:

  • COLOR = (RGB notation as hexideximal #FF0000 (red) or named values RED
  • SIZE = (numbers with units CM, IN, MM, PCT, PT, or PX
  • STYLE = (ITALIC or NORMAL)
  • WEIGHT = (BOLD or NORMAL
  • PATTERN = (SOLID, DASH, SHORTDASH, LONGDASH, DOT, DASHDASHDOT, DASHDOTDOT)
  • THICKNESS = (numbers with units CM, IN, MM, PCT, PT, or PX
  • SYMBOL = (CIRCLE, CIRCLEFILLED, DIAMOND, DIAMONDFILLED,PLUS,SQUARE, SQUAREFILLED, STAR, TRIANGLE)
In [22]:
proc sgplot data=sashelp.stocks
  (where=(date >= "01jan2000"d and stock = "IBM"));
  title "Stock Trend";
  series x=date y=close / LINEATTRS = (THICKNESS = 1MM PATTERN = DASH);
  series x=date y=low;
  series x=date y=high;
  REFLINE 100/ AXIS = Y LABEL= ('$100') TRANSPARENCY=.5;
  INSET 'DOT COM Crash, 2000 - 2002' / POSITION=TOP BORDER;
run;

Paneled Graphics¶

The SGPANEL procedure can be used to create graphics within a panel. The general structure follows as:

PROC SGPANEL DATA=yourdata;
    PANELBY variable;
    plottype;

The plot types are similar to SGPLOT:

  • HBAR
  • VBAR
  • HISTOGRAM
  • LOESS
  • REG
  • SCATTER
  • SERIES

Complete details can be found at: http://support.sas.com/documentation/cdl/en/grstatproc/69716/HTML/default/viewer.htm#p17wwoehcyc6mxn1hpcgxy8ixw6w.htm

In [23]:
proc sgpanel data=sashelp.class; 
    panelby sex / novarname;
    loess x=height y=weight / clm;
run;
